# Todo Conventions

Location: Root-level `todo/` folder; single file: `todo.md`.

Structure:

- Open items (heading at top) - Single numbered list sorted by priority in this order: `[High]`, then `[Med]`, then `[Low]`. Renumber sequentially after any reorder so numbering is always `1..N`. Format: `N. [High] <item name>`.
- Completed items (section below open items) - Use bullets (no numbering), keep completion date in brackets, and include PR status. Format: `- [YYYY-MM-DD] <item name> (PR #123)` or `- [YYYY-MM-DD] <item name> (no PR)`. Sort in descending order by date (newest first). If there are none, use `_(none)_`.
- Detail sections (below the lists) - Include detail sections only for open numbered items, with enough Purpose and Approach so that later instructions like "work on todo item 3" can be executed with full context.

When adding a todo: add the line to Open items with the appropriate tag (`[High]`, `[Med]`, or `[Low]`), then place it in priority order and renumber the open list. Add a matching detail section (Purpose + Approach) below.

When completing a todo: move the line from Open items to Completed items, convert it to completed format with PR status (e.g. `- [2025-03-01] Point card app... (PR #123)` or `... (no PR)`), sort Completed items descending by date, and renumber the open list. Remove the completed item's detail section.

If a completed item included a `[BUG]` tag in Open items, preserve `[BUG]` in the Completed item text (e.g. `- [2026-03-04] [BUG] Fix ... (PR #123)`).

When working on a todo item: read the detail section for that number to get purpose and approach before implementing.
